{"parse":{"title":"Universal grinder","pageid":26260610,"revid":741705374,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">\"Universal sorter\" and \"Universal packager\" redirect here. For other uses of \"sorter\", see <a href=\"/wiki/Sorter_(disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-redirect mw-disambig\" title=\"Sorter (disambiguation)\">Sorter (disambiguation)</a>. For other uses of \"packager\", see <a href=\"/wiki/Packager_(disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-redirect mw-disambig\" title=\"Packager (disambiguation)\">Packager (disambiguation)</a>.</div>\n<table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style ambox-Orphan\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"display: none\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Wiki_letter_w.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Wiki letter w.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/40px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"40\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/60px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/6c/Wiki_letter_w.svg/80px-Wiki_letter_w.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"44\" data-file-height=\"44\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>is an <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Orphan\" title=\"Wikipedia:Orphan\">orphan</a>, as no other articles <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special:Whatlinkshere&amp;target=Universal_grinder&amp;namespace=0\">link to it</a></b>. Please <a href=\"/wiki/Help:Link\" title=\"Help:Link\">introduce links</a> to this page from <span class=\"plainlinks\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Special%3ASearch&amp;redirs=1&amp;search=Universal+grinder&amp;fulltext=Search&amp;ns0=1&amp;title=Special%3ASearch&amp;advanced=1&amp;fulltext=Universal+grinder\">related articles</a></span>; try the <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//edwardbetts.com/find_link?q=Universal_grinder\">Find link tool</a> for suggestions.  <small><i>(October 2015)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Linguistics\" title=\"Linguistics\">linguistics</a>, the term \"<b>universal grinder</b>\" refers to an idea that in some languages, most <a href=\"/wiki/Count_noun\" title=\"Count noun\">count nouns</a> can be used as if they were <a href=\"/wiki/Mass_noun\" title=\"Mass noun\">mass nouns</a>, which causes a slight change in their meaning. The term \"universal grinder\" was first used in print by F. Jeffry Pelletier in 1975, after a personal suggestion by David Lewis.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Related concepts, the <b>universal sorter</b> and <b>universal packager</b> refer to similar processes that allow mass nouns to be used as count nouns.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Universal_grinder\">Universal grinder</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Universal_grinder&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Universal grinder\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The idea of the \"universal grinder\" is that while count nouns usually denote whole, distinct objects (such as <i>a steak</i>, <i>two steaks</i>), the equivalent mass noun connotes a non-distinct quantity of whatever constitutes these objects (<i>some steak</i>). The universal grinder suggests that most count nouns can be used as mass nouns, and the distinct thing named by the noun will be thought of as a general quantity.\n</p><p>While the \"universal grinder\" can be used in many <a href=\"/wiki/Indo-European_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Indo-European language\">Indo-European languages</a>, most particularly <a href=\"/wiki/English_language\" title=\"English language\">English</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Dutch_language\" title=\"Dutch language\">Dutch</a>, it does not apply in all languages; there is considerable cross-linguistic variation in the <a href=\"/wiki/Morphology_(linguistics)\" title=\"Morphology (linguistics)\">morphology</a> and semantics of the mass/count and singular/plural distinctions. For example, bare count nouns in <a href=\"/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese\" title=\"Mandarin Chinese\">Mandarin Chinese</a> do not receive mass interpretations: a sentence such as <i>Qi\u00e1ng-shang d\u014du sh\u00ec g\u01d2u</i> can only be interpreted as 'There are dogs all over the wall,' not as 'There is dog all over the wall.'<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Universal_sorter_and_packager\">Universal sorter and packager</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Universal_grinder&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Universal sorter and packager\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The \"universal sorter\" describes one way in which mass nouns are understood when they are used in the <a href=\"/wiki/Plural\" title=\"Plural\">plural</a>. Harry Bunt suggested the universal sorter in his 1981 doctoral dissertation.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> When an ordinarily uncountable noun such as <i>wine</i> appears with plural form (<i>several wines</i>), it can be understood as referring to various abstract kinds (for example, varieties of wine).<sup id=\"cite_ref-Zhang_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Zhang-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The \"universal packager\" likewise describes how mass nouns are understood when they are used as countable nouns. In this case, the plural noun may be understood as naming individual servings or \"packages\" (e.g. <i>two coffees</i> may mean \"two cups of coffee\"), or as naming abstract kinds (<i>two coffees</i> can also refer to e.g. <a href=\"/wiki/Colombian_coffee\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Colombian coffee\">Colombian coffee</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Indonesian_coffee\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Indonesian coffee\">Indonesian coffee</a>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Some scholars use the phrase <i>universal packager</i> to refer to both the concrete and abstract understanding of plural nouns; others use it to refer only to the concrete sense, and use <i>universal sorter</i> for abstract meaning.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Zhang_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Zhang-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Universal_grinder&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Pelletier, F. Jeffry: <i>Non-singular reference: some preliminaries</i>. In <i>Philosophia</i> Vol. 5 No. 4 Pp. 451\u2013465, October 1975.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Cheng, Lisa L.S., Doetjes, Jenny, and Sybesma, Rint: <i>How universal is the Universal Grinder?</i> In <i>Linguistics in the Netherlands 2008</i>, pp. 50\u201362.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation thesis\">Bunt, Hendrik C. (1981). <i>The formal semantics of mass terms</i> (Thesis). Universiteit van Amsterdam. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/251587734\">251587734</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Adissertation&amp;rft.title=The+formal+semantics+of+mass+terms&amp;rft.inst=Universiteit+van+Amsterdam&amp;rft.date=1981&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F251587734&amp;rft.aulast=Bunt&amp;rft.aufirst=Hendrik+C.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AUniversal+grinder\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Zhang-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Zhang_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Zhang_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Zhang, Niina Ning (2013). <i>Classifier Structures in Mandarin Chinese</i>. De Gruyter. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-3-11-030499-2\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-3-11-030499-2\">978-3-11-030499-2</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Classifier+Structures+in+Mandarin+Chinese&amp;rft.pub=De+Gruyter&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.isbn=978-3-11-030499-2&amp;rft.aulast=Zhang&amp;rft.aufirst=Niina+Ning&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AUniversal+grinder\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Filip, Hana (1999). <i>Aspect, Eventuality Types, and Nominal Reference</i>. Psychology Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a hre